To the Hugentoblers 💛

Dear Jenna Hugee, you are one of my closest and getting to witness you marry the man of your dreams  in your hometown was an incredible blessing. You are steadfast, constant and most loyal. You love, connect and are most intentional with the people in your life and ensure inclusivity is always at the forefront of your friendships and relationship. From the initial moments of this relationship, you ensured to have moments for your friends to get to know your partner. 

Dear Robin Hugee, 
Thank you for loving us (Jenna’s friends) just as your own. For the time you spent planning activities for us all to do together and get to know each other, the dating advice and the times you and Jenna prayed for us in the seasons we were each in. Your love for people is also so evident and pure and honest. 

Together you are, inclusive, people loving, faith-filled and bold. You bring out each other’s strengths and show grace and patience for each other’s downfalls. You have been through many challenges together and about to step into a big season but you continue to lean in, learn and grow together and most importantly you keep God at the forefront of this relationship. 

I could not love a partnership more than this one and I will keep searching “Robin” on insta for years to come until I figure out how to spell this surname right. 🫢

Love,

Your funny gal 💕

2022,

You were full of colour, beautiful people, fresh new things (ones that scared me 🫠), new places, creativity and so much growth… You were also the year I experienced deep pain. Pain so deep that at times the idea of physical pain seemed like a better option than what I was feeling internally.

But you also taught me resilience and will and that happiness is a choice. I started to seek professional help and started weekly counselling. I confided to the few that made me feel safe and as time went by, the dark places started to fill with light and the broken places started to find healing. Mental health is a journey and it takes work. It’s not a one size fits all and yup Instagram isn’t a proper representation of our lives but hey don’t get mad at your neighbour for posting their highlight reels… instead take the time to ask how they truly are and make intentional conversations with the people you love. Be kind to yourself, Give thanks daily, Tell your friends/family “I love you” daily, Be patient because there will be highs and lows and most importantly Trust in Jesus. 

If you are reading this and you find that you can relate. Know that you are Worthy, you are Seen, you are Loved and you are never alone. 🧡 2023, I am excited for you! 

#blurbsbystef

“Braving the Wilderness” by @brenebrown 

This book was lent to me a day before what would be a very challenging week and little did I know that it would bring me so much light and breakthrough. 

Belonging; This has always been a re-occurring thing in my life. The only non-academic in my family who chose the creative route, born and raised in a country where asians were the minority and so experienced cat calling, the “Ching chong” yells from a very young age and then fast forward to our family’s big move to Canada at the age of 12 where I had a heavy as French accent and dressed like an island girl in the city of Toronto. 🤦🏻‍♀️I found many ways to cover up the longing feeling of belonging and spent most of my years fitting in vs. belonging not knowing there was a huge difference between the two and that this lack of discernment would cause some major hurdles in my adult years. 

So here I am sharing my favourite takeaways from this good read about belonging: 

Strong back, soft front;
Being courageous to stand for what you believe in but still having a soft front for those with opposing views and being more curious.

“Tell me more”; one of the bravest things you can ask someone sharing their opposing views with you. 

Lastly, True belonging; Sharing your most authentic self with the World while finding sacredness in both being a part of something and standing alone. 

You belonged to that moment with yourself that Sunday afternoon, you belonged to that moment you had with the stranger who walked passed and smiled at you, you belonged to that moment where you ugly cried with a friend watching a sappy chick flick, you also belonged to that moment you had a challenging but intentional chat with that person at work you didn’t get along with. The World becomes a much brighter place when we start to notice all the places, all the people and all the moments we have belonged to and still have yet to belong to.✨😌 #blurbsbystef

This year, one of my big goals/focuses is saving $$$ while still allowing room for fun times. I’ve got a list of what I’ve been doing so far that I’d love to share with you but I wanted to kick things off with a FUN tip because well, if you’re in Australia, it’s now summer and after two years of lockdowns/constant rain, it’s finally time to enjoy the summer. So cue: BYO restaurants! There are surprisingly many here in Sydney and it takes a quick and easy “BYO restaurants near me” search to find a large list with a wide range of cuisine options. This one was a bit of a treat as I’d been wanting to try out the popular/super aesthetic spot @seansbondi for a while now and so I took my bestie and a bottle of @grantburgewines Pinot Noir Chardonnay Rosé from @danmurphys with us and we got to have the full experience - a 3 course menu with vino while saving a little $$$ (note that the corkage fee is $35 here, a bit higher than most but we still saved as we split it between the two of us). 

The Pinot Noir Chardonnay Rosé paired so well with the menu as it’s not only a refreshing option but also very light on the palette which helps compliment a wide range of cuisines. We had the duck salad, fresh green pasta, roasted chicken and pistachio ice cream and chocolate mousse for dessert, still drooling 🤤 Definitely recommend trying this saving tip for upcoming dates, girl’s night, boy’s night etc.! 🕺🏻🥂 #danmurphys #sponsored

Part 1
“There is beauty in the In-between” 

Two weeks ago, I found myself in an all too familiar situation. Another workplace closing down; one that held dreams, hopes and long-term goals. I wanted to take the time to share this in between moment with you because many of us (myself included) often put so much emphasis on the starting point and end point that we often forget about the in-between; The place where growth happens and in my situation where my faith was being tested. Wish i could tell you that I navigated this well but in reality fear and doubt crept in and felt paralyzed with the thought of looking for a new job and the scramble for what this would mean for my current visa. I spiralled even more when I realized that there was no support or financial aid from the government for international residents and the recommendation given was “you must go back to your country if you cannot find new work” (I mean probably makes sense but hard to hear eek🫠). I was so consumed by these thoughts and feelings that I was missing the blooming that was already taking place in the in-between. People fighting for me when I did not have it in me to fight; they drop off meals including wine at your door, they do extensive visa research for you, they shout you coffees, they send you a daily message “how is today feeling?”, they pick you up for some fresh air, they pray with you and they scramble up over a week’s worth of rent money 🥹. This is when you start to want to fight, when people who aren’t blood related fight for you but the thing is I never had to fight because all along God wanted me to surrender it all to him and not have to carry the weight of this. He was showing me his Love in the form of community. I am so grateful for my chosen family here in Australia and as well for my friends and family back home routing me on. I am so amazed by the generosity and kindness I’ve been shown in this in-between season and it is worth any bit of visa, financial, career and mental stress. 😌💛

Part 2 Coming because He’s not done yet 🥲

#blurbsbystef

Part 2 (In case you missed it, refer to my last post for part 1 ☺️) 

In a moment of surrender, I felt God say to me “continue to create” and I felt such a peace come after this. 

My art has always been an outlet for me to find rest, peace and stillness. It was an unexpected blessing for me during the two years in covid when I was able to make a living through it and after the two years, I had decided that my art would be more a passion on the side and a way for me to give back and bless others. Fast forward to this in between season and I had the opportunity to start creating from a place of uncertainty but full surrender. What I didn’t know was the big plans He had for me during this in-between season. I had called my brother the day after I had this clear message about “creating again” and he excitedly mentioned to me that he would love to treat me to a trip to the Philippines in two weeks time where he would love my help with one of the biggest initiatives he has ever organized; hosting a community dinner for Easter for the 1000 people of a small town called Maya in the Philippines. It all clicked for me then! I was to use my art to support my brother with this initiative and for the very first time would be able to physically take a part of it!!! 🥹 (because well, in -between jobs!) So this collection titled “The In-between series” concepted long ago at a time where it never felt right to put out was completed during this in-between season where it had the opportunity to flourish to its purpose. So on April 8th, I will be flying over to join my brother in the Philippines and the community dinner will be taking place on April 15th! I am honoured to get this opportunity at a time like this and feeling beyond blessed for such a generous and kind hearted brother! 💛

If you’d like to view the full collection and support this initiative, head over to my website www.bysteffifoo.com

Ps. I got offered a job offer yesterday (just after my “Part 1” post 🫢🥹) #blurbsbystef

Maya Park Homes 💛

I fell in love with the people of this town and am inspired by their display of kindness and care towards each other while exemplifying what true community is all about. 

I got to stay in this town for a few days over my trip and I can’t deny that it was not a stretching experience for me. Let’s just say that creepy crawlers indoors (🐁🪳🕷️)is not my portion 🫠. It didn’t take long though for me to experience feeling so welcomed in this community and the discomfort soon decreased and I felt safe here.

I had always wanted to have an experience like this one and many times let fear stop me from turning this yearn into reality. This time it felt like it was the perfect timing for me to say yes and my heart was ready to have this experience. 

I am so grateful for all the friends and family who partnered with me on this journey and sent encouragement as well as donated to the cause to make this an incredible turnout. My brother especially who organized this entire initiative and invited me to take part. Together we were able to feed over 800 people of this town and were able to provide to 5 of the most vulnerable families with groceries and daily essentials.

If you ever have the opportunity, I say do it and don’t let the “I’m not strong enough or I’m not ready” lies get to you because kindness and love does surpass any feelings of fear and discomfort and this is what I was left with from this experience. 

This is one I will never forget and forever cherish and hope to have more opportunities like these in my future 🥲

-Stef #blurbsbystef

Last March of this year I released my “in-between” collection - A collection ideated and inspired by the in-between place, the place where fear and uncertainty meet trust and faith if we make space for them to meet. If you are new here and haven’t been following my journey this year, this was also where I had the beautiful opportunity to partner with my brother and his partner to go to this tiny town called Maya in the Philippines and feed over 800 people as well provide groceries for a total of 5 families while we were there. This is all thanks to everyone who partnered with me and purchased my art as well as generously donated. I was so touched by the people I got to meet on this trip and their joy found in the simplest things in life. 

As my art was a complete blessing for me for the two years during Covid where the events industry was at a complete halt, I always told myself that my art would be a way to be kind and provide to others and after a few months break, I’m excited to kick off my art again and partner with people who not only share an appreciation for art but also have a heart for people. So for the next 6 weeks until Christmas, 50% of all my art purchases will be going towards getting water connection in the homes of as many families as we can for the people of Maya, Philippines. My brother and I both saw this need while we were there and have done the research to find out how to do this and how much it will cost. $150 to get the initial water connection and $10 a month to have water running throughout a home and we would love to get each family 3 months of water in addition to the initial connection to allow for them to be able to continue to sustain this on their own. 

So head on over to my website (link in bio) and choose between my collection or a completely custom piece. 

I truly couldn’t do any of this without you guys and my friends and family who inspire me daily to continue to do this so thank you so much from my gooey mushy heart. 🥹💙

Home is coming together 🥹💚The last missing pieces after a 4 month wait— ft. My beautiful Togo custom couches.

Re: Living presently: I used to live on a temporary or reward focused approach. “Only invest in items once you know you’ll be there for x years”, “treat yourself after you’ve passed this test or received this grade”, “only book this trip if you’ve made this x amount of money” etc. I was raised to have this mentality and so bigger purchases/decisions were always a massive debate and felt weighty. They were dependent on two things;  1. Do I deserve this and 2. Is this the right timing and so unconsciously started to always live in the next rather than the now and things I did became reward based rather than simply living. 

Here I am 5 years in this country which was very much supposed to be temporary and it’s only this year that I started to see the importance of investing in my present just as much and if not more than my future. It truly does something to your daily posture and I’ve noticed the weight it has lifted off me so here I am simply just doing things that make me happy, visa still underdetermined, next step unknown but I’m making decisions for my now and it has been liberating. I have to remind myself that it was a similar posture that got me to move to Australia on my own with all things unknown and it has been my best decision yet. 🥲

Anyway I cannot wait to share this cutie little home with many of you in the next few months and I so encourage you to start making some more present moment decisions and truly trust in the process. 💛 #mylvngrm

2023 - You were quite the turbulent year for me 🎢 but I look back at it and there are so many good things to be grateful for 🥲🫠 Here’s a little recap: 

This was the year I lost a job I loved, and gained a new one I loved, the year I had to jump on a new visa abruptly due to the unexpected, the year I moved out of my 4+ year home with my bestie and moved closer to the ocean, the year I felt deep loneliness and the year I met an incredible group of gals who all craved solid community while being keen to start a 🎾 club, the year I took a life changing trip to the beautiful Philippines, the year I gained the funniest gang of workmates and a 🥝 desk neighbour with an equal love of snacking, the year one of my besties got married and sissy got engaged! and just before the year ended, a new special person snuck in 🧑🏻..

This was the year Brokenness and Joy were felt, where Pain and Healing took place and Fear and Courage were simultaneously at battle. Mentally, it was also one of the hardest years and at times that I felt my lowest, I am most grateful for my close few; the ones I called my “safe people” who helped me navigate this year. The ones I turned to in the late hours of the night where my anxiety felt paralyzing and suffocating, the ones I could tell what was truly on my mind even though I felt crazy at times for having these thoughts. The ones who would go for a walk with me and just listen, send me a daily text asking how my heart and mind were feeling. I am truly so grateful for these safe few in my life, for knowing you I am better for it. 💙

So to recap:

-Change, good OR bad can be a lot of stress on a person, give yourself time and space to transition through the seasons
-Realness and vulnerability, they take place in the behind the scenes of life so check up on your friends and don’t use socials to assume (it is okay Ps. to use this platform as your highlight reel, just make sure you are doing the real work on the side 😌)
-Comparison is the thief of happiness; we are ALL going through our own struggles
-The more we try to control, the less space we leave for God to work in our lives ☝🏼
-Find your safe few and let them love you 💙
